\paragraph*{Proof}

(\Leftarrow) Let $\chi:X_{n}\to \mathbb R$ be a constant function. Since $\chi$ is constant on $X_{n}$, it is also constant on each cell of $X_{n}$, for any cell of $X_{n}$ is either empty or is a convex set, and hence, any point of it lies in exactly one of these cells. Thus, in particular, $\chi$ can be extended to a $(n+1)$-cellular function $\bar\chi:\mathbb R^{n+1} \to \mathbb R$.

(\Rightarrow) Let $\chi:\mathbb R^{n+1} \to \mathbb R$ be a $(n+1)$-cellular function. Then, for any $x\in \mathbb R^n$, we have $\chi(x,0)=0$. Therefore, the subset $\{x\in \mathbb R^n: \chi(x)=0\}$ is closed in $\mathbb R^n$, and is contained in each cell of $X_n$. Therefore, it is its own closure, and must equal $X_n$. Hence, $\chi$ is constant on $X_n$.


\end{lemmata}


